	<h1>Choosing a blood pressure monitor</h1>
	
	<p>It is important to ensure that your blood pressure monitor is accurate and the right monitor for you.</p>
	
	<h4>Use an arm blood pressure monitor</h4>
		<p>Blood pressure monitors that wrap a cuff around your upper arm are generally more accurate than wrist or finger monitors.</p>
	
	<h4>Use a clinically validated monitor</h4>
		<p>Make sure that the home blood pressure monitor you choose has been listed as 'clinically validated' for accuracy by the British Hypertension Society. This means that the monitor has gone through a series of tests to make sure it gives results that you can trust. Visit the <a href='http://www.bhsoc.org//index.php?cID=246' target='_blank'>British Hypertension Society's website</a> for a list of validated monitors.</p>

	<h4>Use the right cuff size</h4>
		<p>An upper-arm blood pressure monitor will come with a cuff that you need to wrap around your arm. If you use a cuff that is the wrong size for you, your blood pressure reading will not be correct. Measure around your upper arm at the midpoint between your shoulder and elbow, and choose your cuff size from the table below.</p>
