		<p>Most home blood pressure monitors will come with a medium-sized cuff. You may have to order a different-sized cuff separately.</p>

	<h4>Choose a monitor to suit your budget</h4>
		<p>All you need to accurately measure your blood pressure at home is a clinically validated monitor and pen and paper to record the results. Spending more money often brings more features such as a built-in memory, but these are not essential.</p>
	
	<h4>Keep your monitor calibrated</h4>
		<p>Monitors generally need to be re-calibrated about once every 2 years to ensure they continue to give accurate results. This usually involves returning the monitor to the manufacturer, who may charge a fee for this service.</p>

